After a Navi uses a battlechip, they need to jack out to make that chip usable again, or to change your chip folder. **Folders may not have duplicate chips, or more than 1 Megachip.** This command can display info on Battlechips.

2019-06-06 05:49:24	Prog's Playhouse	#general	Mr. Prog#5635	Battlechips are one-use attacks that NetOps slot into their PETs. Your PET's folder space is determined by your **Navi's Mind + Navi's Info + 2**. When making a new character, pick starter battlechips equal to your **NetOp's Mind + NetOp's Info + 2**. After a Navi uses a battlechip, they need to jack out to make that chip usable again, or to change your chip folder. **Folders may not have duplicate chips, or more than 1 Megachip.** This command can display info on Battlechips.

2019-06-12 22:56:07	Prog's Playhouse	#botspeak	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. n\-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves.

2019-06-13 03:56:24	Merry Mancer Games	#netbattle-club	DonJentleman#0559	>help parry	
2019-06-13 03:56:24	Merry Mancer Games	#netbattle-club	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2019-06-14 03:35:16	Merry Mancer Games	#free-play-2	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2019-06-19 18:37:53	my campaign (UNNAMED)	#bot-commands	GSK Bladez#7356	>help parry	
2019-06-19 18:37:53	my campaign (UNNAMED)	#bot-commands	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2019-06-26 02:38:54	Merry Mancer Games	#netbattle-club	GSK Bladez#7356	>help parry	
2019-06-26 02:38:55	Merry Mancer Games	#netbattle-club	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2019-07-22 06:10:16	Merry Mancer Games	#free-play-1	GSK Bladez#7356	>help parry	
2019-07-22 06:10:16	Merry Mancer Games	#free-play-1	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2019-07-30 01:36:52	Tabletopping	#netbattlers	GSK Bladez#7356	>help chip	
2019-07-30 01:36:52	Tabletopping	#netbattlers	Mr. Prog#5635	Battle Chips are one-use attacks that NetOps slot into their PETs. Your PET's folder space is determined by your **Navi's Mind + Navi's Info + 2**. When making a new character, pick starter Battle Chips equal to your **NetOp's Mind + NetOp's Info + 2**. After a Navi uses a Battle Chip, they need to jack out to make that Battle Chip usable again, or to change your Battle Chip folder. **Folders may not have duplicate Battle Chips, or more than 1 Mega Chip.** This command can display info on Battle Chips.	
2019-07-30 01:37:03	Tabletopping	#netbattlers	GSK Bladez#7356	>help parry	
2019-07-30 01:37:03	Tabletopping	#netbattlers	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2019-08-14 06:24:27	Merry Mancer Games	#free-play-1	GSK Bladez#7356	>help parry	
2019-08-14 06:24:27	Merry Mancer Games	#free-play-1	Mr. Prog#5635	A character may attempt to counter a melee attack with their own, called a **__parry__**. Before your opponent rolls an attack, declare whether you would like to parry. If so, make an opposed roll (in most cases, Strength). Whoever as the most hits wins the parry, and the loser takes a point of damage per hit rolled by the winner (not reduced by loser's hits). _In the event of a tie, both parties must either **escalate** or **back down**._ \n \n_-If both **back out** nobody takes any damage. \n \n-If one **backs out** and one **escalates**, the parry ends, and the one backing out takes the winner's damage.\n \n-If both **escalate**, they make the opposed roll again, adding new totals to previous accumulated damage. If there is another tie, it continues until someone comes on top, or the parry resolves._

2020-08-21 23:49:17	FishbowlTest	#general	Iza#0395	>help parry	
2020-08-21 23:49:18	FishbowlTest	#general	ProgTest#5253	A character can try to counter a melee attack with a melee attack of their own, called a **__parry__**. Both parties roll using the appropriate skill, likely Strength. Whoever has the most hits wins, and the loser takes damage equal to the winner’s roll. This damage is not reduced by how many hits the loser rolled.\n\nIf the two characters tie, they have a choice: back out or escalate. Both parties should declare this simultaneously. If both back out, nobody takes damage and the parry ends. If one escalates and the other backs out, the parry ends and the one that backed out is the loser. If both parties escalate, roll to melee attack each other again. Whoever rolls higher is the winner, unless they tie; in which case, the cycle continues until someone comes out on top. \n\nUnless both back out, when the parry ends, the loser takes damage equal to the winner’s strongest attack. However, if the loser backed out, they take half the damage they normally would, rounded up.
